# Comparison Operators
Comparison operators are used to compare two values and return a boolean result. The common comparison operators in
JavaScript include:
- Equality (`==`): Returns true if the values of the operands are equal, after type coercion.
- Strict equality (`===`): Returns true if the values and types of the operands are equal, without type coercion.

`(coercion means JavaScript will try to convert the values to a common type before comparing them.)`

Example:
```javascript
console.log(5 == '5'); // true (type coercion occurs)
console.log(5 === '5'); // false (no type coercion, different types)
console.log(.1 + 0.2 == 0.3); // true (type coercion occurs)
console.log(.1 + 0.2 === 0.3); // false (no type coercion, different types)
console.log(.15 + 0.15 == 0.3); // true (type coercion occurs)
```
Why does `.1 + 0.2 === 0.3` return false? but .1 + 0.2 == 0.3 returns true?
- This is because of the way JavaScript handles floating-point arithmetic. 
- When you perform the operation `.1 + 0.2`, it results in a value that is very close to 0.3, but not exactly equal to it due to the limitations of representing decimal numbers in binary. 

When you use the `==` operator, JavaScript performs type coercion and considers the two values equal because they are close enough. However, when you use the `===` operator, it checks for both value and type equality without coercion, and since the result of `.1 + 0.2` is not exactly equal to 0.3, it returns false.
