# TYPE CASTING
- Type casting is the process of converting a value from one data type to another for a specific purpose. In JavaScript, type casting can be done explicitly or implicitly.

- `Rule 1`: 0 is falsy, while any non-zero number is truthy.
```javascript
console.log(0 == false); // true (type coercion occurs)
console.log(1 == true); // true (type coercion occurs)

console.log(0 == true); // false (type coercion occurs)
console.log(1 == false); // false (type coercion occurs)
```
- `Rule 2`: An empty string is falsy, while any non-empty string is truthy.
```javascript
console.log((1>4) == ""); // false
console.log((1>4) == "Hello"); // false (type coercion occurs, but the empty string is falsy)
console.log(("Hello")); // true
```
- `Rule 3`: null and undefined are falsy. But when use them in a single line, they are truthy.
```javascript 
console.log(null == false); // false
console.log(undefined == false); // false
console.log(null == undefined); // true (because null || undefined evaluates to undefined, which is falsy, but the Boolean function converts it to true)
```
- `Rule 4`: NaN (Not a Number) is falsy. Even if you try to convert it to a boolean, it will still be falsy.
```javascript
console.log(NaN == NaN); // false
console.log(123 == NaN); // false
```
