# Array Data Type
- An array is a special type of object that stores any type of data in an ordered collection. Arrays are created using square brackets `[]` and can hold multiple values.

- It has dynamic size, which means you can add or remove elements from an array without having to specify its size in advance. 

- Contiguous memory location, which allows for efficient access to elements using their index.

- Indexing starts from 0, which means the first element of an array is accessed using index 0, the second element using index 1, and so on.

- Ordered Memory Allocation, which means that the elements of an array are stored in contiguous memory locations, allowing for efficient access and manipulation of the array elements.

- Mutable, which means you can change the values of elements in an array after it has been created.
 - >   (inbuilt functions that is used to change the values of elements in an array are `push()`, `pop()`, `shift()`, `unshift()`, `splice()`, etc.)

- Non-primitive data type, which means that arrays are objects and can hold references to other objects or values.

# Properties and methods of arrays include:
- `length`: Returns the number of elements in the array.
- `push()`: Adds one or more elements to the end of the array and returns the new length of the array.
- `pop()`: Removes the last element from the array and returns that element.
- `shift()`: Removes the first element from the array and returns that element.
- `unshift()`: Adds one or more elements to the beginning of the array and returns the new length of the array.
- `indexOf()`: Returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present.
- `slice()`: Returns a shallow copy of a portion of an array into a new array object.
- `splice()`: Changes the contents of an array by removing or replacing existing elements and/or adding new elements in place.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CRUD operations on arrays:
- Create: You can create an array using square brackets `[]` and add elements to it
- Read: You can access elements of an array using their index
- Update: You can update elements of an array by assigning a new value to a specific index
- Delete: You can remove elements from an array using methods like `pop()`, `shift()`, or `splice()`

# Example of CRUD operations on arrays:
```javascript
// Create
let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"];

// Read
console.log(fruits[0]); // Output: "apple"

// Update
fruits[1] = "blueberry";
console.log(fruits); // Output: ["apple", "blueberry", "cherry"]

unshift() method is used to add an element at the beginning of the array

fruits.unshift("orange");
console.log(fruits); // Output: ["orange", "apple", "blueberry", "cherry"]

push() method is used to add an element at the end of the array
fruits.push("grape");
console.log(fruits); // Output: ["orange", "apple", "blueberry", "cherry", "grape"]



// Delete
fruits.pop(); // Removes the last element
console.log(fruits); // Output: ["orange", "apple", "blueberry", "cherry"]

shift() method is used to remove the first element of the array
fruits.shift(); // Removes the first element
console.log(fruits); // Output: ["apple", "blueberry", "cherry"]

// Using splice() to remove an element at a specific index
fruits.splice(1, 1); // Removes 1 element at index 1
console.log(fruits); // Output: ["apple", "cherry"]
```
